## 3. Microbiology and Infectious Diseases

### 3.1 Infectious Diseases and Global Health Impact

Infectious diseases caused by microorganisms remain leading causes of morbidity and mortality worldwide. Lower respiratory infections, HIV/AIDS, malaria, diarrheal diseases, and tuberculosis collectively cause millions of deaths annually, disproportionately affecting developing countries ([Antranik, n.d.](https://antranik.org/impact-of-microbes-on-human-life/)).

Emerging infectious diseases, driven by factors such as international travel, climate change, antimicrobial misuse, and population dynamics, present ongoing challenges. The global interconnectedness facilitates rapid spread of pathogens, exemplified by multidrug-resistant tuberculosis and pandemic influenza threats.

### 3.2 Microbial Evolution and Resistance

Microbial populations evolve rapidly due to high replication rates and genetic exchange, leading to antigenic variation and antibiotic resistance. Horizontal gene transfer via plasmids, bacteriophages, and transposons accelerates dissemination of resistance traits. This evolutionary arms race complicates infection control and necessitates novel therapeutic and preventive approaches ([Baron et al., 2018](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.humic.2018.08.005)).

